Title : Lamina monopolar cell
Text : '''Lamina monopolar cells''' are a class of neurons in the most peripheral [[neuropil]] of the [[arthropod visual system]], the [[lamina (neuropil)|lamina]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cajal|first=S.R.|author2=Sanchez, D. |title=Contribución al conocimiento de los centros nerviosos de los insectos. Parte I Retina y centros opticos.|journal=Trab. Lab. Invest. Biol. Univ. Madrid|year=1915|volume=13|pages=1–168|doi=10.5962/bhl.title.37839}}</ref> Most insects, including flies, have five distinct classes lamina monopolar cells: L1, L2, L3, L4, and L5.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fischbach|first=KF|author2=Dittrich, AP|title=The optic lobe of Drosophila melanogaster. I. A Golgi analysis of wild-type structure. Cell Tissue Res.|journal=Cell and Tissue Research|year=1989|volume=258|issue=3|pages=441–475|doi=10.1007/bf00218858}}</ref> L1, L2, L3, receive direct synaptic input from the photoreceptors in the lamina, and send axons into the second-order neuropil of the visual system, the medulla.

